claim: As noted in the Preferred Reporting Items for Systematic Reviews and Meta-Analyses (PRISMA) flow diagram in Figure 1, the initial search produced 25,230 references after duplicates were removed and 10,651 met the initial screening criteria; 4693 of these articles were published between 2008 and 2015.
title: Figure 1.
caption: Preferred Reporting Items for Systematic Reviews and Meta-Analyses (PRISMA) flow diagram.

claim: Photographs most commonly included genitals (48.4% [293/605]), chest or breasts (21.7% [131/605]), skin donor site (primarily forearm or leg) (10.1% [61/605]), and face (8.1% [49/605]) (see Figure 2).
title: Figure 2.
caption: Characteristics of medical photographs.

claim: As noted in Figure 3, the ability to locate a PDF of the article online through open access, Researchgate.net, or Academia.edu is one factor that contributes to the availability of at least one image from the article on Google Images (OR 2.99, 95% CI 1.20-7.45).
title: Figure 3.
caption: Odds ratios indicating likelihood of clinical photographs being included in Google Images search results.
